00:00:44.150 --> 00:00:46.270
We're going to try to deal
with a bunch of different

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:51.450
topics today, some of which are
a little bit philosophical

00:00:51.450 --> 00:00:55.360
saying, what is probability
really?

00:00:55.360 --> 00:01:00.220
You are supposed to have taken
a course in probability, but

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:04.760
unfortunately courses in
probability are almost always

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:08.080
courses in how to solve
well-posed problems.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:11.750
The big problem in probability
theory, and particularly

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:18.040
stochastic processes is not
so much how do you solve

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:20.290
well-posed problems.

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:22.320
Anybody can do that.

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:28.040
Or anybody who has a little bit
of background can do it.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:33.550
The hard problem is finding
the right models for a

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:35.060
real-world problem.

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:36.980
I will call these real-world
problems.

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:40.730
I hate people who call things
real-world because they sound

00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:43.310
like they dislike theory
or something.

00:01:43.310 --> 00:01:47.380
It's the only word I can think
of though, because physical

00:01:47.380 --> 00:01:51.200
world is no longer adequate
because so much of the

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:55.190
applications of probability are
to all sorts of different

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:58.670
things, not having to do with
the physical world very much,

00:01:58.670 --> 00:02:03.400
but having to do with things
like the business world, or

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:07.850
the economic world, or the
biological world, or all of

00:02:07.850 --> 00:02:10.190
these things.

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:15.990
So real-world is just a code
word we'll use to distinguish

00:02:15.990 --> 00:02:21.280
theory from anything real that
you might have to deal with.

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:23.830
Theory is very nice
because theory--

00:02:23.830 --> 00:02:25.670
everything is specified.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:27.800
There's a right answer
to everything.

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:29.640
There is a wrong
answer usually.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.350
But there's at least
one right answer.

00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:34.420
And most of us like those
things because

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:35.620
they're very specific.

00:02:35.620 --> 00:02:39.250
People go into engineering and
science very often because

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:42.150
they don't like the
uncertainty of a

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:44.130
lot of other fields.

00:02:44.130 --> 00:02:48.170
The problem is as soon as you
go into probability theory,

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:51.560
you're moving away from that
safe region where everything

00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:55.260
is specified, and you're moving
into a region where

00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:58.360
things, in fact, are not very
well-specified and you have to

00:02:58.360 --> 00:02:59.900
be careful about it.

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:02.670
OK, so first we're going to talk
about probability in the

00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:06.150
real world and probability as
a branch of mathematics.

00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:07.840
Then we're going to
say what discrete

00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:10.200
stochastic processes are.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:14.850
Then we're going to talk just a
very, very little bit about

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:17.140
the processes we're
going to study.

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:21.430
If you want to see more
of that, you have two

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:22.530
chapters of the notes.

00:03:22.530 --> 00:03:23.720
You can look at them.

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:26.260
You can look at the
table of contents.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:30.910
And more than that, if you look
at my website, you will

00:03:30.910 --> 00:03:33.490
see the notes for all the other
chapters if you want to

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:36.500
read ahead or if you want to
really find out what kinds of

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.660
things we're going to talk about
and what kinds of things

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:40.320
we're not going to talk about.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:42.180
Then we're going to talk
about when, where,

00:03:42.180 --> 00:03:44.000
and how is this useful?

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.385
The short answer to that is
it's useful everywhere.

00:03:47.385 --> 00:03:49.930
But we'll have to
see why that is.

00:03:49.930 --> 00:03:51.620
Then we're going to talk
about the axioms

00:03:51.620 --> 00:03:53.150
of probability theory.

00:03:53.150 --> 00:03:58.310
You cannot take any elementary
course in probability, or even

00:03:58.310 --> 00:04:03.690
in statistics, without seeing
the axioms of probability.

00:04:03.690 --> 00:04:06.740
And in almost all of those
cases, and in almost all of

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:10.350
the graduate courses I've
seen, you see them, they

00:04:10.350 --> 00:04:14.340
disappear, and suddenly you're
solving problems in whatever

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:16.470
way you can, and the
axioms have nothing

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:18.040
to do with it anymore.

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:21.390
So we're going to see that, in
fact, the axioms do have

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:23.680
something to do with this.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:29.940
Those of you who want to be
real engineers and not

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:31.990
mathematicians, you'll
find this a little

00:04:31.990 --> 00:04:33.910
uncomfortable at times.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:37.050
We are going to be
proving things.

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:40.940
And you will have to
get used to that.

00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:43.560
And I'll try to convince you
of why it's important to be

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:45.180
able to prove things.

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:47.470
Then we're going on to a
review of probability,

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:48.930
independent events,

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:51.850
experiments, and random variables.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:53.100
So that's what we'll do today.

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:59.990
Incidentally, this course
started about--

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:02.730
must've been 25 years
ago or so.

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:07.790
I started it because we had a
huge number of students at MIT

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:12.120
who had been interested in
communication and control, and

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:15.170
who were suddenly starting to
get interested in networks.

00:05:15.170 --> 00:05:17.780
And there were all sorts of
queuing problems that they had

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:19.490
to deal with every day.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:21.950
And they started to read
about queuing theory.

00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:25.580
and it was the most disjointed,
crazy theory in

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:28.690
the world where there were
1,000 different kinds of

00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:30.720
queues and each one
of them had to be

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.960
treated in its own way.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:36.130
And we realized that stochastic
processes was the

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.620
right way to tie all of
that together, so we

00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:39.620
started this course.

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:44.090
And we made it mostly discrete
so it would deal primarily

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:46.330
with network type
applications.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:51.120
As things have grown, it now
deals with a whole lot more

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:52.320
applications.

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:56.170
And we'll see how that
works later on.

00:05:56.170 --> 00:06:00.230
OK, how did probability get
started in the real world?

00:06:00.230 --> 00:06:02.540
Well, there were games of chance
that everybody was

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:03.690
interested in.

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:06.120
People really like to gamble.

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:07.980
I don't know why.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:09.720
I don't like to gamble
that much.

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:11.740
I would rather be certain
about things.

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:14.330
But most people love
to gamble.

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:16.730
And most people have an
intuitive sense of what

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:18.690
probability is about.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.790
I mean, eight-year-old kids,
when they start to learn to

00:06:22.790 --> 00:06:24.750
play games of chance--

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:26.410
and there are all sorts
of board games

00:06:26.410 --> 00:06:27.870
that involve chance.

00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:29.740
These kids, if they're
bright--

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:33.780
and I'm sure you people fall
into that category--

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:37.230
they immediately start to figure
out what the odds are.

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:40.390
I mean, how many of you have
never thought about what the

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:43.640
odds are in some
gambling game?

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:46.320
OK, that makes my point.

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:50.630
So all of you understand this
at an intuitive level.

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:54.310
But what makes games of chance
easier to deal with than all

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:59.340
the other issues where we have
uncertainty in life?

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:03.340
Well, games of chance are
inherently repeatable.

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:07.100
You play a game of chance and
you play many, many hands, or

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:10.740
many, many throws, or
many, many trials.

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:14.470
And after many, many trials of
what's essentially the same

00:07:14.470 --> 00:07:18.080
experiment, you start to get
a sense of what relative

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:18.960
frequencies are.

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:22.210
You start to get a sense of what
the odds are because of

00:07:22.210 --> 00:07:26.110
doing this repeatedly.

00:07:26.110 --> 00:07:30.500
So games of chance are easy to
use probability on because

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:31.890
they are repeatable.

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:35.820
You have essentially the same
thing going on each time, but

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:38.090
each time there's a
different answer.

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:41.190
You flip a coin and sometimes
it comes up heads and

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:43.630
sometimes it comes up tails.

00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:49.310
So in fact, we have to figure
out how to deal with that fact

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:50.650
that there is uncertainty
there.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:54.350
I'll talk about that in
just another minute.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:58.600
But anyway, most of life's
decisions involve uncertainty.

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:03.920
I mean, for all of you, when you
go into a PhD program, you

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:04.960
have two problems.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:06.930
Am I going to enjoy this?

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:09.070
And you don't know whether
you're going to enjoy it

00:08:09.070 --> 00:08:12.210
because not until you really
get into it do you have a

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:15.540
sense of whether this set of
problems you're dealing with

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:20.060
is something that you
like to deal with.

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:26.330
And the only way you can do
that is to make guesses.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.100
You come up with likelihoods.

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:29.400
There's some likelihood.

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:34.039
There's a risk cost-benefit
that you deal with.

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:38.270
And in life, risk cost-benefits
are always based

00:08:38.270 --> 00:08:41.650
on some sense of what the
likelihood of something is.

00:08:41.650 --> 00:08:42.710
Now, what is a likelihood?

00:08:42.710 --> 00:08:44.360
A likelihood is just
a probability.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:46.980
It's a synonym for
probability.

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:50.060
When you get into the
mathematics of probability,

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:52.950
likelihood has a special
meaning to it.

00:08:52.950 --> 00:08:57.080
But in the real world,
likelihood is just a word you

00:08:57.080 --> 00:08:59.540
use when you don't want to let
people know that you're really

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:01.790
talking about probabilities.

00:09:01.790 --> 00:09:07.710
OK, so that's where we are.

