00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:52.470
Important point about
probability.

00:11:52.470 --> 00:11:54.810
Think about flipping a coin.

00:11:54.810 --> 00:11:56.920
I'm going to talk about
flipping coins a

00:11:56.920 --> 00:11:58.500
great deal this term.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:02.300
It's an absolutely trivial
topic, but it's important

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:07.300
because when you understand
deep things about a large

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:10.530
subject, the best way to
understand them is to

00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:13.420
understand them in terms of the
most trivial examples you

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:14.880
can think of.

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:18.770
Now, when you flip a coin, the
outcome-- heads or tails--

00:12:18.770 --> 00:12:24.020
really depends on the initial
velocity, the orientation of

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:27.310
the person flipping it, or the
machine flipping it, the coin

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:29.960
surfaces, the ground surface.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.480
And after you put all of those
things into a careful

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:36.800
equation, you will know whether
the coin is going to

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:39.080
come up heads or tails.

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:41.860
I don't think quantum theory
has anything to do with

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:43.620
something as big as a coin.

00:12:43.620 --> 00:12:45.210
I might be wrong.

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:46.630
I've never looked into it.

00:12:46.630 --> 00:12:48.200
And frankly, I don't care.

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:50.870
Because the point that I'm
trying to make is that

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:53.410
flipping a coin, and many of
the things that you view as

00:12:53.410 --> 00:12:57.170
random, when you look at them
in a slightly different way,

00:12:57.170 --> 00:12:59.020
are not random.

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:01.390
There's a big field in
communication called data

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:02.810
compression.

00:13:02.810 --> 00:13:07.270
And data compression is based on
random models for the data,

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:09.480
which is going to
be compressed.

00:13:09.480 --> 00:13:13.070
Now, what I'm saying here today
is by no means random.

00:13:13.070 --> 00:13:14.900
Or maybe it is partly random.

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:17.910
Maybe it's coming out of a
random mind, I don't know.

00:13:17.910 --> 00:13:23.725
But all of the data we try to
compress to the people who

00:13:23.725 --> 00:13:27.260
have created that data, it's
not random at all.

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:30.710
If you study the data
carefully enough--

00:13:30.710 --> 00:13:33.510
I mean, code breakers and people
like that are extremely

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:37.550
good at sorting out what the
meaning is in something, which

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:41.230
cannot be done by data
compression techniques at all.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:45.280
So the point is, when you're
doing data compression, you

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:48.010
model the data as being random
and having certain

00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:49.570
characteristics.

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.800
But it really isn't.

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:54.130
So the model is no good.

00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:56.550
When you get to more important
questions--

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:59.950
well, data compression is
an important question.

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:02.530
When you ask, what's the
probability of another

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:05.790
catastrophic oil spill
in the next year?

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:08.040
Or you ask the question, what's
the probability that

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:10.140
Google stock will double
in five years?

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:12.580
That's less important,
but it's still

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:15.630
important to many people.

00:14:15.630 --> 00:14:16.880
How do you model that?

00:14:19.410 --> 00:14:22.300
Understanding probability
theory, understanding all the

00:14:22.300 --> 00:14:26.500
mathematics of this is not going
to help you model this.

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:29.880
Now, why do I make such
a big deal about this?

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:33.910
Well, there have been a number
of times in the last 10 or 15

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:38.480
years when the whole financial
system of the world has almost

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:43.200
been destroyed by very,
very bright PhDs.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:47.680
Many of them coming from
electrical engineering.

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:50.010
Most of whom are really
superb at

00:14:50.010 --> 00:14:52.580
understanding probability theory.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:55.490
And they have used their
probability theory to analyze

00:14:55.490 --> 00:14:58.640
risk and other things
in investments.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:00.630
And what has happened?

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:03.100
They do very well for a while.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:06.050
Suddenly they do so well that
they think they can borrow all

00:15:06.050 --> 00:15:08.750
sorts of money and risk other
people's money as

00:15:08.750 --> 00:15:09.610
well as their own.

00:15:09.610 --> 00:15:13.080
In fact, they try to do that
right from the beginning.

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:16.030
And then suddenly, the whole
thing collapses.

00:15:16.030 --> 00:15:18.240
Because their models
are no damn good.

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:21.220
There's nothing wrong with their
mathematics, it's that

00:15:21.220 --> 00:15:22.770
their models are no good.

00:15:22.770 --> 00:15:26.710
So please, especially if you're
going to do something

00:15:26.710 --> 00:15:28.940
important in your lives--

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:32.410
if you're just going to write
papers in engineering

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:36.000
journals, maybe it's
all right.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.940
But if you're going to make
decisions about things, please

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:43.060
spend some time thinking about
the probability models that

00:15:43.060 --> 00:15:47.890
you come up because this
is vitally important.

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:49.110
OK, what's probability?

00:15:49.110 --> 00:15:50.630
It's a branch of mathematics.

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:53.870
Now we're into something
that's more familiar,

00:15:53.870 --> 00:15:57.420
something that's simpler,
something we can deal with.

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:02.340
You might be uncomfortable
with what

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:04.280
probability really means.

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:08.660
And all probability books, all
stochastic process books are

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:10.080
uncomfortable with this.

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:14.250
Feller is the best book
in probability

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:17.260
there's ever been written.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.090
Any question you have, he
probably has the answer to it.

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:26.960
When you look at what he says
about real-world probability,

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:31.150
the modeling issues, he's an
extraordinarily bright guy.

00:16:31.150 --> 00:16:33.900
And he spent some time
thinking about this.

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:35.360
But you read it and you realize

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:38.630
that it's pure nonsense.

00:16:38.630 --> 00:16:40.710
So please, take my
word for it.

00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:46.780
Don't assume that real-world
probability is something

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:49.070
you're going to learn about from
other people because you

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.120
can't trust what any
of them say.

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:53.800
It's something you have to think
through for yourselves,

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:56.410
and we'll talk more about
this as we go.

00:16:56.410 --> 00:16:59.200
But now, when we get into
mathematics, that's fine.

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:00.440
We just create models.

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:03.090
And once we have the model,
we just use it.

00:17:03.090 --> 00:17:06.680
We have standard models for
all sorts of different

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:08.260
standard problems.

00:17:08.260 --> 00:17:11.890
When you talk about coin
tossing, what almost everyone

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:16.339
means is not this crazy thing I
was just talking about where

00:17:16.339 --> 00:17:20.800
you have an initial angular
momentum when you flip a coin

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:22.300
and all of that stuff.

00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:25.990
It's a purely mathematical model
where a coin is flipped

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:28.440
and with probability one half
it comes up heads and with

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:32.070
probability one half
it comes up tails.

00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:36.050
OK, students are given a
well-specified model, and they

00:17:36.050 --> 00:17:37.840
calculate various things.

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:40.370
This is in mathematical
probability.

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:43.710
Heads and tails are equiprobable
in that system.

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:46.510
Subsequent tosses
are independent.

00:17:46.510 --> 00:17:49.630
Here's a little bit
of cynicism.

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:52.700
I apologize for insulting
you people with it.

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:57.430
I apologize to any faculty
member who later reads this.

00:17:57.430 --> 00:18:01.300
And I particularly apologize to
businessmen and government

00:18:01.300 --> 00:18:03.070
people who might read it.

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:06.840
Students compute, professors
write papers, business and

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:10.290
government leaders obtain
questionable models and data

00:18:10.290 --> 00:18:12.540
on which they can
blame failures.

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:16.070
Most cynical towards business
leaders because business

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:19.220
leaders often hire
consultants.

00:18:19.220 --> 00:18:23.300
Not so much to learn what to do,
but so they have excuses

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:26.430
when what they do doesn't
work out right.

00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:30.220
When I say the students compute,
what I mean is this

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:34.030
in almost all the courses you've
taken up until now--

00:18:34.030 --> 00:18:36.390
and in this course also--

00:18:36.390 --> 00:18:38.220
what you're going
to be doing is

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:39.820
solving well-posed problems.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:43.730
You solve well-posed exercises
because that's a good way to

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:46.340
understand what the
mathematics of

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:48.410
the subject is about.

00:18:48.410 --> 00:18:51.780
Don't think that that's
the only part of it.

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:54.690
If that's the only thing you're
doing, you might as

00:18:54.690 --> 00:18:55.830
well not waste your time.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:57.600
You might as well do
something else.

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:00.730
You might as well go out and
shovel snow today instead of

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:02.860
trying to learn about
probability theory.

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:06.960
It's more pleasant to learn
about probability theory.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:11.010
OK, the use of probability
models has two major

00:19:11.010 --> 00:19:13.300
problems with it.

00:19:13.300 --> 00:19:16.400
The first problem is, how do
you make a model for a

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:18.600
real-world problem?

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:23.930
And a partial answer is, learn
about estimation and decisions

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:26.150
in the context of
standard models.

00:19:26.150 --> 00:19:31.870
In other words, decisions and
estimation inside a completely

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:34.880
mathematical framework.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:36.480
Then you learn a great
deal about the

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:39.140
real-world problem itself.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:43.880
Not about the mathematics of it,
but about how you actually

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:46.270
understand what's going on.

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:49.740
If you talk to somebody
who is a superb

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:53.030
architect in any field--

00:19:53.030 --> 00:19:57.420
networks, computer systems,
control systems, anything--

00:19:57.420 --> 00:19:59.500
what are you going to find?

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:03.630
You're not going to find huge,
involved sets of equations

00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:06.700
that they're going to use to
explain something to you.

00:20:06.700 --> 00:20:09.780
They're going to pick at-- if
there any good, they're going

00:20:09.780 --> 00:20:12.480
to take this big problem, and
they're going to take your

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:14.560
issue with this big problem.

00:20:14.560 --> 00:20:17.700
And they're going to find the
one or two really important

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:21.790
things that tell you something
that you have to know.

00:20:21.790 --> 00:20:24.350
And that's what you want to
get out of this course.

00:20:24.350 --> 00:20:28.150
You want to get the ability to
take all of the chat, put it

00:20:28.150 --> 00:20:31.920
all together, and be able to
say one or two important

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:35.220
things which is really
necessary.

00:20:35.220 --> 00:20:37.670
That's where you're going to.

00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:41.300
Before you get there, you'll
take low-level jobs in various

00:20:41.300 --> 00:20:43.570
companies and you'll compute
a lot of things.

00:20:43.570 --> 00:20:45.310
You'll simulate a
lot of things.

00:20:45.310 --> 00:20:47.540
You'll deal with a
lot of detail.

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.170
Eventually, you're going to get
to the point where you've

00:20:50.170 --> 00:20:51.920
got to make major decisions.

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:53.800
And you want to be
ready for it.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:55.580
OK, that's enough philosophy.

00:20:55.580 --> 00:20:58.830
I will try to give no more
philosophy today, except when

00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:00.080
I get pushed into it.

00:21:09.776 --> 00:21:15.930
OK, one of the problems in this
problem of finding a good

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:18.880
model is that no model
is perfect.

00:21:18.880 --> 00:21:22.130
Namely, what happens is you
keep finding more and more

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:25.050
complicated models, which
deal with more

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:26.990
and more of the issues.

00:21:26.990 --> 00:21:31.100
And as you deal with them,
things get more complicated.

00:21:31.100 --> 00:21:34.380
You're more down in the
level of details and

00:21:34.380 --> 00:21:35.640
you're finding out less.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:39.850
So you want to find some sort of
match between a model that

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:42.880
tells you something and a model
which is complicated

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:45.180
enough to deal with
the issues.

00:21:45.180 --> 00:21:49.740
There's a beautiful quote by
Alfred North Whitehead.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.960
I don't know whether you've
ever heard of Whitehead.

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:55.160
You've probably heard of
Bertrand Russell, who was both

00:21:55.160 --> 00:22:01.000
a great logician and a great
philosopher, and had a lot to

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.590
do with the origins
of set theory.

00:22:04.590 --> 00:22:08.570
Whitehead and Russell together,
wrote this massive

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:14.160
book around the turn of the last
century between the 1900s

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:18.630
and the 2000s called Principia
Mathematica where they try to

00:22:18.630 --> 00:22:22.220
resolve all of the paradoxes
which were coming up in

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:23.420
mathematics.

00:22:23.420 --> 00:22:27.920
And Whitehead's general
philosophical comment was,

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:33.580
"Seek simplicity and
distrust it."

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:37.025
Now, every time I look at
that, I say, why in hell

00:22:37.025 --> 00:22:41.640
didn't he say, seek simplicity
and question it?

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:43.850
I mean, you all hear about
questioning authority, of

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:46.520
course, and that's
important to do.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:50.310
Why when you find a simple model
for something should you

00:22:50.310 --> 00:22:52.420
distrust it?

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:55.670
Well, the reason is
psychological.

00:22:55.670 --> 00:22:59.660
If you find a simple model for
something and you question it,

00:22:59.660 --> 00:23:03.260
you have an enormous
psychological bias towards not

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:04.550
giving up the simple model.

00:23:04.550 --> 00:23:07.340
You want to keep that
simple model.

00:23:07.340 --> 00:23:11.270
And therefore, it takes an
enormous amount of evidence

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:13.770
before you're going to
give something out.

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:15.530
Whitehead said something
more than that.

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:19.400
He said, "Seek simplicity
and distrust it."

00:23:19.400 --> 00:23:21.940
Now, why do I talk about the
philosophy of science when

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:24.110
we're trying to learn about
probability theory?

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:27.480
Well, probability theory is
a mathematical theory.

00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:29.960
It's the basis for a great
deal of science.

00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:35.050
And it's the place where
modeling is most difficult.

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:37.600
Scientific questions in most
areas, if there's no

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:41.140
probability or uncertainty
involved, you just do an

00:23:41.140 --> 00:23:44.170
experiment that tells
you the answer.

00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:46.330
You might not do it carefully
enough and then 10 other

00:23:46.330 --> 00:23:47.380
people do it.

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:49.670
And finally, everybody
agrees, this is the

00:23:49.670 --> 00:23:51.140
answer to that problem.

00:23:51.140 --> 00:23:53.930
In probability, it ain't
that simple.

00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:57.720
And that's why one has to focus
on this a little more

00:23:57.720 --> 00:23:59.740
than usual.

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:04.730
The second problem is, how do
you make a probability model

00:24:04.730 --> 00:24:06.430
that has no hidden
paradoxes in it?

00:24:06.430 --> 00:24:11.130
In other words, when you make
a mathematical model, how do

00:24:11.130 --> 00:24:14.930
you make sure that it really
is well-posed?

00:24:14.930 --> 00:24:17.490
How do you make sure that when
you solve a problem in that

00:24:17.490 --> 00:24:20.400
mathematical model that you
don't come to something that

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:22.820
doesn't make any sense?

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:27.060
Well, everyone's answer to that
is you use Kolmogorov's

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:29.030
axioms of probability.

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:33.190
Because back in 1933, Kolmogorov
published this

00:24:33.190 --> 00:24:35.410
little thin book.

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:37.370
Those of you who are interested
in the history of

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:40.620
science probably ought
to read it.

00:24:40.620 --> 00:24:43.530
You will find you only
understand the first five

00:24:43.530 --> 00:24:46.330
pages the first time
you look at it.

00:24:46.330 --> 00:24:49.170
But it's worthwhile doing that
because here was one of the

00:24:49.170 --> 00:24:53.930
truly great minds of the
early 20th century.

00:24:53.930 --> 00:24:58.260
And he took everything he knew
about probability, which was a

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:01.630
whole lot more than I know
certainly, and a whole lot

00:25:01.630 --> 00:25:04.740
more than anybody else at the
time knew, and he collapsed it

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:07.100
into these very simple axioms.

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:12.330
And he said, if you obey these
axioms in a model that you use

00:25:12.330 --> 00:25:16.580
in probability, those axioms
will keep you out of any

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:18.270
paradoxes at all.

00:25:18.270 --> 00:25:21.690
And then, he showed why that
was and he showed how the

00:25:21.690 --> 00:25:23.845
axioms could be used
and so forth.

00:25:23.845 --> 00:25:25.990
So we're going to spend a little
bit of time talking

00:25:25.990 --> 00:25:27.790
about them today.

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:31.850
OK, quickly, what is a discrete
stochastic process?

00:25:31.850 --> 00:25:34.180
Well, a stochastic process--

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:36.100
you've been talking
about probability.

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:41.690
And you might be getting the
idea that I'm just using the

00:25:41.690 --> 00:25:45.670
name "stochastic processes" as
a foil for talking about what

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:48.210
I really love, which
is the probability.

00:25:48.210 --> 00:25:51.210
And there's a certain amount
of truth to that.

00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:56.360
But stochastic processes are
special types of probability

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:02.680
models where the sample points
represent functions in time.

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:05.420
In other words, when we're
dealing with a probability

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:07.270
model, the basis of
a probability

00:26:07.270 --> 00:26:08.750
model is a sample space.

00:26:08.750 --> 00:26:12.220
It's the set of possible things
that might happen.

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:15.550
And you can reduce that to the
sample points, which are the

00:26:15.550 --> 00:26:20.010
indivisible, little, tiny crumbs
of what happens when

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:20.790
you do an experiment.

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:24.080
It's the thing which specifies
everything that can be

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:29.040
specified in that model
of that experiment.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:31.670
OK, when you get to a stochastic
process, what

00:26:31.670 --> 00:26:35.600
you're doing is you're looking
at a situation in which these

00:26:35.600 --> 00:26:40.560
sample points, the solutions to
what happens is, in fact, a

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:44.550
whole sequence of random
variables in time.

00:26:49.475 --> 00:26:53.410
And what that means is instead
of looking at just a vector of

00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:56.070
random variables, you're going
to be looking at a whole

00:26:56.070 --> 00:26:59.040
sequence of random variables.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:03.890
Now, what is different about a
vector of a very large number

00:27:03.890 --> 00:27:06.580
of random variables
and an infinite

00:27:06.580 --> 00:27:09.280
sequence of random variables?

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:14.150
Well, from an engineering
standpoint, not very much.

00:27:14.150 --> 00:27:18.060
I mean, there's nothing you can
do to actually look at an

00:27:18.060 --> 00:27:22.160
infinite sequence of
random variables.

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:26.380
If you start out at the Big Bang
and you carry it on to

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:29.220
what you might imagine is the
time when the sun explodes or

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:32.380
something, that's a finite
amount of time.

00:27:32.380 --> 00:27:37.330
And if you imagine how fast
you can observe things,

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:39.530
there's a finite number
of random

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:41.280
variables you might observe.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:44.670
All these models we're going to
be dealing with get outside

00:27:44.670 --> 00:27:47.960
or that realm, and they deal
with something that starts

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:50.200
infinitely far in the
past and goes

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:52.760
infinitely far in the future.

00:27:52.760 --> 00:27:55.860
It doesn't make much
sense, does it?

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:58.610
But then look at the
alternative.

00:27:58.610 --> 00:28:01.800
You built a device which
you're going to sell to

00:28:01.800 --> 00:28:04.840
people, and which they're
going to use.

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:06.660
And you know they're only going
to use it three or four

00:28:06.660 --> 00:28:09.970
year until something
better comes along.

00:28:09.970 --> 00:28:13.410
But do you want to build in to
everything you're doing the

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:15.790
idea that it's going to be
obsolete in three years?

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:17.390
No.

00:28:17.390 --> 00:28:21.510
You want to design this thing
so, in fact, it will work for

00:28:21.510 --> 00:28:24.300
an essentially arbitrary
amount of time.

00:28:24.300 --> 00:28:27.160
And therefore, you make a
mathematical model of it.

00:28:27.160 --> 00:28:30.860
You look at what happens over
an infinite span of time.

00:28:30.860 --> 00:28:34.330
So whenever we get into
mathematics, we always go to

00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:36.290
an infinite number of
things rather than a

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:39.130
finite number of things.

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:42.420
Now, discrete stochastic
processes are those where the

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:45.560
random variables are
discrete in time.

00:28:45.560 --> 00:28:47.820
Namely, a finite number
of possible outcomes

00:28:47.820 --> 00:28:49.880
from each of them.

00:28:49.880 --> 00:28:55.340
Or the set of possible sample
values is discrete.

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:57.000
What does that mean?

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:00.090
It doesn't mean a whole lot when
you really start asking

00:29:00.090 --> 00:29:02.680
detailed questions about this.

00:29:02.680 --> 00:29:07.420
What it means is, I want to talk
about a particular kind

00:29:07.420 --> 00:29:08.760
of stochastic processes.

00:29:11.290 --> 00:29:15.740
And it's a class of processes
which will be more than we can

00:29:15.740 --> 00:29:17.600
deal with in one term.

00:29:17.600 --> 00:29:20.900
And I want to exclude certain
processes, like noise

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:24.890
processes, because we don't have
time to do both of them.

00:29:24.890 --> 00:29:27.980
So don't worry too much about
exactly what a discrete

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:29.230
stochastic process is.

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:34.930
It's whatever we want to call
it when we deal with it.

00:29:38.220 --> 00:29:39.630
Oops.

00:29:39.630 --> 00:29:43.252
Oh, where am I?

00:29:43.252 --> 00:29:47.180
Oh, I wanted to talk about the
different processes we're

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:49.540
going to study.

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:51.310
The first kind of process
is what we

00:29:51.310 --> 00:29:54.310
call a counting process.

00:29:54.310 --> 00:29:57.230
The sample points in the
process-- remember, a sample

00:29:57.230 --> 00:30:00.660
point specifies everything
about an experiment.

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:03.660
It tells you every
little detail.

00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:07.010
And the sample points here
in counting processes are

00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:08.980
sequences of arrivals.

00:30:08.980 --> 00:30:13.140
This is a very useful idea in
dealing with queuing systems

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:15.260
because queuing systems
have arrivals.

00:30:15.260 --> 00:30:16.670
They have departures.

00:30:16.670 --> 00:30:20.120
They have rules for how the
arrivals get processed before

00:30:20.120 --> 00:30:22.300
they get spit out.

00:30:22.300 --> 00:30:26.220
And a big part of that is
studying first the arrival

00:30:26.220 --> 00:30:29.420
process, then we study the
departure process.

00:30:29.420 --> 00:30:32.330
We study how to put
them together.

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:35.730
And when we get to chapter 2 of
the notes, we're going to

00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:39.400
be studying Poisson processes,
which are in a sense, the

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:43.020
perfect discrete stochastic
process.

00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:45.660
It's like coin tossing
in probability.

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:47.930
Everything that might
be true with a

00:30:47.930 --> 00:30:50.530
Poisson process is true.

00:30:50.530 --> 00:30:52.830
The only things that aren't
true are the things that

00:30:52.830 --> 00:30:55.130
obviously can't be true.

00:30:55.130 --> 00:30:57.280
And we'll find out why
that is and how that

00:30:57.280 --> 00:30:59.150
works a little later.

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:00.750
We're then going to
study renewal

00:31:00.750 --> 00:31:03.950
processes in chapter 4.

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:07.510
We're going to put Markov
chains in between.

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:09.800
And you'll see why
when we do it.

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:13.960
And renewal processes are a more
complicated kind of thing

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:15.810
than Poisson processes.

00:31:15.810 --> 00:31:18.440
And there's no point confusing
you at this point saying what

00:31:18.440 --> 00:31:20.800
the difference is, so I won't.

00:31:20.800 --> 00:31:25.690
Markov processes
are processes.

00:31:25.690 --> 00:31:29.590
In other words, the sequences
in time of things where what

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:34.270
happens in the future depends
on what happens in the past,

00:31:34.270 --> 00:31:36.820
only through the state
at the present.

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:39.140
In other words, if you can
specify the state in the

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:41.760
present, you can forget about
everything in the past.

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:49.750
If you have those kinds of
processes around, you don't

00:31:49.750 --> 00:31:54.030
have to study history at all,
which would be very nice.

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:58.110
But unfortunately, not all
processes behave that way.

00:31:58.110 --> 00:32:00.860
When you do the modeling to try
to find out what the state

00:32:00.860 --> 00:32:03.650
is, which is what you have to
know at the present, you find

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:06.050
out there's a lot of
history involved.

00:32:06.050 --> 00:32:08.470
OK, finally, we're going to talk
about random wa;ls and

00:32:08.470 --> 00:32:09.640
martingales.

00:32:09.640 --> 00:32:12.030
I'm not going to even say
what a random walks or

